'''Shoban''' (諸蕃) is a term used in [[ancient]] [[Japan]] to refer to the countries of the [[Korean Peninsula]] known as the [[Three Han]]—including [[Goguryeo]] (高句麗, Kōkuri), [[Baekje]] (百済, Kudara), and [[Silla]] (新羅, Shiragi)—as well as China. The [[Wakun]] (Japanese reading) for this term is "tonari no kuni" ("neighboring countries") or "moromoro no ebisu" ("various barbarians"). The term was also used to refer to [[immigrant clans]] of [[Toraijin]] origin from the Three Han, such as the [[Hata clan]] and the {{ill|Baekje no Ōkimi clan|ja|百済王氏}}.
Mentions of "Shoban" appear in multiple entries in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}},'' such as the 11th month of the 3rd year of [[Emperor Seinei]]'s reign ({{ill|482|ja|482年}}). During the [[Ritsuryō system]], administrative offices like the ''{{ill|Genbanryō|ja|玄蕃寮}}'' were established, and terms such as "Shoban," "Ban," and "Bankoku" were frequently used. After the unification of the Korean Peninsula by [[Silla]] in the latter half of the [[7th century]], "Shoban" came to refer specifically to Silla in certain cases.
While the exact beginning of the usage of "Shoban" to denote immigrants is unclear, the annotation of the ''Nihon Shoki'' known as the "Kōnin Shiki" mentions the existence of a document titled ''Shoban Zatsuseiki'' ("Records of Various Foreign Names"). The earliest confirmed instance is in the ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録}},'' compiled in [[815]] during the {{ill|Kōnin era|ja|弘仁}}, where "Shoban" (not "Banbetsu") was used as a designation alongside ''{{ill|Kōbetsu|ja|皇別}}'' and ''{{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別}}.'' It was defined as referring to "clans of the Three Han."
In the [[Meiji period]], under the [[kazoku]] system's {{ill|Clan system (Kazoku)|ja|宗族制 (華族)}}, families of Shoban lineage were classified as "Gaibetsu" ("foreign origin").
