While the exact beginning of the usage of "Shoban" to denote immigrants is unclear, the annotation of the ''Nihon Shoki'' known as the "Kōnin Shiki" mentions the existence of a document titled ''Shoban Zatsuseiki'' ("Records of Various Foreign Names"). The earliest confirmed instance is in the ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}},'' compiled in [[815]] during the {{ill|Kōnin era|ja|弘仁}}, where "Shoban" (not "Banbetsu") was used as a designation alongside ''{{ill|Kōbetsu|ja|皇別}}'' and ''{{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別}}.'' It was defined as referring to "clans of the Three Han."
In the [[Meiji period]], under the [[kazoku]] system's {{ill|Clan system (Kazoku)|ja|宗族制 (華族)}}, families of Shoban lineage were classified as "Gaibetsu" ("foreign origin").
