While the exact beginning of the usage of "Shoban" to denote immigrants is unclear, the annotation of the ''Nihon Shoki'' known as the "Kōnin Shiki" mentions the existence of a document titled ''Shoban Zatsuseiki'' ("Records of Various Foreign Names"). The earliest confirmed instance is in the ''[[:en:Shinsen Shōjiroku|Shinsen Shōjiroku]],'' compiled in [[815]] during the [[:en:Kōnin (era)|Kōnin era]], where "Shoban" (not "Banbetsu") was used as a designation alongside ''{{ill|Kōbetsu|ja|皇別|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōbetsu|qq=}}'' and ''{{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別|1=Shinbetsu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|qq=}}.'' It was defined as referring to "clans of the Three Han."
In the [[Meiji period]], under the [[kazoku]] system's {{ill|Clan system (Kazoku)|ja|宗族制 (華族)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Clan system (Kazoku)|qq=}}, families of Shoban lineage were classified as "Gaibetsu" ("foreign origin").
