[[sn:Shoban]]
[[ja:諸蕃]] [[sn:hoban]] [[Category:前近代の朝鮮系日本人]] [[Category:日本の律令制]] [[Category:朝鮮の別名]] [[Category:Toraijin]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[ko:제번]] [[zh-min-nan:Chu-hoan]]

'''Shoban''' (諸蕃) is a term used in [[:en:Ancient history|Ancient history]] [[:en:Japan|Japan]] to refer to the countries of the [[:en:Korea|Korea]] known as the [[Three Han]]—including [[:en:Goguryeo|Goguryeo]] (高句麗, Kōkuri), [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]] (百済, Kudara), and [[Silla]] (新羅, Shiragi)—as well as China. The [[Wakun]] (Japanese reading) for this term is "tonari no kuni" ("neighboring countries") or "moromoro no ebisu" ("various barbarians"). The term was also used to refer to [[immigrant clans]] of [[Toraijin]] origin from the Three Han, such as the [[:en:Hata clan|Hata clan]] and the [[:en:Kudara no Konikishi clan|Baekje no Ōkimi clan]].
Mentions of "Shoban" appear in multiple entries in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]],'' such as the 11th month of the 3rd year of [[:en:Emperor Seinei|Emperor Seinei]]'s reign ([[:en:482|482]]). During the [[Ritsuryō system]], administrative offices like the ''{{ill|Genbanryō|ja|玄蕃寮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genbanryō|qq=}}'' were established, and terms such as "Shoban," "Ban," and "Bankoku" were frequently used. After the unification of the Korean Peninsula by [[Silla]] in the latter half of the [[:en:7th century|7th century]], "Shoban" came to refer specifically to Silla in certain cases.
While the exact beginning of the usage of "Shoban" to denote immigrants is unclear, the annotation of the ''Nihon Shoki'' known as the "Kōnin Shiki" mentions the existence of a document titled ''Shoban Zatsuseiki'' ("Records of Various Foreign Names"). The earliest confirmed instance is in the ''[[:en:Shinsen Shōjiroku|Shinsen Shōjiroku]],'' compiled in [[:en:815|815]] during the [[:en:Kōnin (era)|Kōnin era]], where "Shoban" (not "Banbetsu") was used as a designation alongside ''{{ill|Kōbetsu|ja|皇別|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōbetsu|qq=}}'' and ''{{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別|1=Shinbetsu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|qq=}}.'' It was defined as referring to "clans of the Three Han."
In the [[Meiji period]], under the [[kazoku]] system's {{ill|Clan system (Kazoku)|ja|宗族制 (華族)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Clan system (Kazoku)|qq=}}, families of Shoban lineage were classified as "Gaibetsu" ("foreign origin").
